column1: 02s6900002PAHTeAAP5006900003K1FnrAAF[#176479] urgent : Checksum Issue upgradation of Artifactory to major versionHi Krishna

I have tried to replicate this behavior in our lab. I have installed Artifactory version 6.5.2 and upgraded to 7.18.6. Pulled few npm packages from npm registry where by default Checksum messages gets displayed.
I have not fixed the "Fix checksum" message and upgraded.
Below is the screenshot from Artifactory version 6.5.2.
Below is the screenshot from Artifactory version 7.18.6.
There is no change in the behavior.
Testcase2: I have fixed the "Fix checksum" message for another artifact and upgraded.
Below is the screenshot from Artifactory version 6.5.2.
Below is the screenshot from Artifactory version 7.18.6.

column2: there is no change. As upgrade does not touch this table
column3: there would not be any changes.

column1: I have further checked with our R&D team to check if there is a way to fix the message for all artirats.
In order to fix this message
column2: you may run the below command to set it.

column1: 2. Take a backup of nodes tables.

UPDATE nodes SET sha1_original='NO_ORIG' WHERE node_type = 1 and ((sha1_original IS NULL) OR (sha1_actual IS NULL) OR (sha1_original != 'NO_ORIG' AND sha1_original != sha1_actual))UPDATE nodes SET md5_original='NO_ORIG' WHERE node_type = 1 and ((md5_original IS NULL) OR (md5_actual IS NULL) OR (md5_original != 'NO_ORIG' AND md5_original != md5_actual))

Note : I would like to emphasize that seeing the "Fix checksum message" is has per the design and has no affect on Artifactory's functinality as Artifactory never uses the cheskums what client published. It always depends on the cheksums what it generates during the pull from internet or push from local.
Hope this helps to overcome the message. Let us know if you have any further queries. Looking forward to your response.

column1: 02s6900002PAHVGAA55006900003jaigLAAQ[#184095] federated repository failing due to following errorHi Sangamesh
Thank you for working with me tonight. After some testing
column2: we concluded that you have encountered a known bug with Federated Repositories and that a rolling reboot might solve the issue. Just in case
column3: I have escalated this ticket to be reviewed by the developers.

column2: we found the same 400 HTTP errors were encountered even if the Include/Exclude pattern was reset to "**/*". We also found that the other three Federated Repositories were not working
column3: we tried copying an "Ubuntu" image to these Federated Repos with no luck.

column2: and found that you have encountered an internal bug: RTDEV-24571 - Federated Repository is failing to propagate files from Source with 400 error on Source and Null on Destination

column1: The suggested workaround is to try a rolling reboot of both Source and Target Artifactory
column2: we could reboot the AWS Artifactory but not the Colo Artifactory on our call tonight. The plan is to reboot the Colo Artifactory at around 9 PM PST.

column1: In the meantime I am escalating this ticket to get further steps to try. Expect an update from us soon with regards to the escalation
column2: please let me know if the reboot helps or does not.

column1: 02s6900002PAHYKAA55006900003YgF1AAAV[#183333] Getting manifest unknown: The named manifest is not known to the registry error when trying to pull images from Dockerhub via ArtifactoryHello Akash
Thank you for joining me in a session today.

column2: we reviewed the issue and tried a few things to get a better understanding of what may be causing the docker requests to not be sent with credentials.

column1: We tried some manual curl commands to obtain the docker token and saw that we were able to retrieve and pull images as expected with the token/user.
The only mentioned networking object in between the docker client and the Artifactory instance was a Netscaler Load Balancer.
When we attempted to perform a docker login through the HA URL (through the Load Balancer) we see on Artifactory's side that the credentials are not sent and the user is being read as anonymous.

We were able to test the IP of the Artifactory instance directly to art1. The IP was added as an insecure registry in the docker daemon and the pull succeeded with credentials to docker-hub repository.

column2: we saw that no logs were being written to art1 but we found that the logback.xml was mis-modified so we added the logback.xml from art2 which was working and we saw the docker logs with the user as expected.

column1: We further tested the HA URL by shutting down art2 so the traffic gets redirected to art1 and saw that docker requests were being read as anonymous in art1.

There is not anything wrong with the Artifactory configurations and Artifactory is working properly. The Load Balancer is causing the issue and we suspect that the credentials are getting stripped there (i.e. maybe some header is being removed).

To investigate further we will need to look at the Load Balancer configuration to see what it may be doing to cause this issue. Akash mentioned that this is being managed by another team and getting the information may take some time. I will await this information.
I will also let you know if I discover anything that may point to what in Netscaler may be causing this but for further investigation
column2: more information from Netscaler will be needed.

column2: since the error "Error while trying to connect to local router at address 'http://localhost:8046/access':connection refused" is the only indication
column3: we suspected that the port 8046 is available for service but the service couldn't get to listen at the particular port which could have occurred due to existing old process IDs.

column2: we have decided to perform a clean restart of the service and observed the member node coming up after the restart. We were able to access the Artifactory member node.

we have observed the primary node is not available while we were troubleshooting the member node issue. You have checked with the team internally and confirmed that there were some changes done in regards to permissions on the primary node by the team. While trying to perform a restart of the primary node
column3: it returned a 'permission denied' error and from the artifactory-service.log
column4: we observed an 'access denied' error against a particular access-client library file.

column1: We have compared the permissions assigned to the files in specific between the working and the non-working instances and it appeared to be the same. As we couldn't get to the root cause of the issue on the primary node
column2: you have confirmed that you will get in touch with the team internally to verify the permissions.

column1: We would mark this support case as closed
column2: if any further assistance is needed in the future
column3: you may always reach out to JFrog Support. Thank you once again for your patience and understanding.

column1: To: Wai Loon Tan (DHL IT Services) <wailoon.tan@dhl.com>
Subject: [#183569] Big problem with nuget virtual repository
Thank you for waiting while I was checking on this matter internally.
The possible workaround is setting the concerned Nuget remote repository to be 'offline'  ( link<https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Remote+Repositories#:~:text=URLs%20are%20supported.-
column2: Offline
column3: -If%20set%2C%20this> ) so the request triggered for resolving the Nuget packages will not be reaching the upstream remote repository and will be looking for the packages within the cached files.  However
column4: it might cause some issues when builds depend on newer versions that are not cached.  Another possible workaround is configuring the Nuget client to use the V3 protocol instead of the default V2.

column1: 02s6900002PAHakAAH5006900003jaixbAAA[#184108] JFROG Xray blocking low and medium vulnerabilitiesHello Nate
Thank you for joining me in a session today.

column2: we saw that for the artifacts being blocked Xray was blocking them not because of the violations but because they were being read as unscanned. After we disabled the policy set to block unscanned we saw that we could download the artifact.
however
column3: is a requirement. So we investigated deeper into this.

column1: We found that reindexing the artifacts manually through the rest API endpoint here resolved the issue but because there were many artifacts it is not feasible to do this one by one.

There is no way to reindex an entire repository so we had to look for alternatives. One proposed workaround was to delete all the artifacts in the repository and recopy them so that they would be removed from the database and reindexed when they were copied back. You will be performing this operation and getting back to me. (Note please allow some time after deleting the artifacts before recopying them in for the database to remove the entries in the backend)
If this solution does not work we will have to look at running an external script. Let me know how the test goes.

column2: we'll have users report that Artifactory is down. Upon browsing to the UI
column3: we'll receive a "friendly" 500 error message (from Artifactory UI
column4: not a direct 500 from the web server). The only way we've found to resolve this is to restart the Artifactory service (one at a time) on each of the cluster nodes. Once all service instances have been restarted
column5: the system functions normally again. The frequency of this greatly varies. Sometimes
column6: it happens once a week. Sometimes
column7: everything will be fine for a month. However
column9: and we'd like to get to the root of it / solve it. Please let me know what additional information you need from me to troubleshoot. Thank you!

column1: 02s6900002PAHbOAAX5006900003jajDxAAIRe: [#184126] Workaround for installing and using X-Ray with artifactory version 6.xWe wanted to know the workaround for installing and using X-Ray with artifactory version 6.x
We are having artifactory HA configuration

column2: Kyle

column1: Thank you for joining me in a session today.

column2: we looked closer at this issue. We found that metadata being returned for a particular package contained an incorrect URL containing "_relative" when retrieved from the virtual repository.
engineering
column3: but we were unable to replicate the issue there and it functioned as expected without a 404 on the npm install command.

column1: We noticed that the package.json in the .npm repository did later contain the correct URLs but the URL retrieved from the api/npm endpoint still contained the "_relative" url.
I believe that you may be running into RTDEV-24405
column2: 'Cover additional NPM "_relative"-specific cases'
column3: an internal JIRA where the '_relative' rewrite was not occurring properly for the metadata and resulting in 404s like we saw in our session.

column1: This JIRA fix was released in a later Artifactory version 7.27.X.
As updating Artifactory is not possible without prior planning and baking we went ahead with a workaround to get your developers unblocked.
We created a local npm repository containing the package (and all of its versions). We added it to priority resolution and to the npm virtual repository. After this
column2: we were able to resolve the npm packages without issue.

column1: We only noted that the issue was happening with the 'adp-react-components' package and its versions so we only copied those artifacts from the remote repository but the same workaround can be done if you encounter this issue for other packages.
Let me know if you have any further questions regarding this ticket or if you are able to plan an update for Artifactory to the latest 7.27.X to see if this resolves the issue or if it does not
column2: to continue troubleshooting the cause.

I ran into multiple separate issues
column2: but I think removing the DataDir value worked.

column1: For the gist of it (after removing the postgresqlDataDir value)
column2: the postgres database had trouble starting up after a pod restart after an import. It looked like also user/groups/permissions were unable to be imported. I knew we were using a different postgres database docker image than the default one in the helm chart
column3: so I revised it to use the default bitnami/postgresql database image. That allowed it to boot up the first time
column4: but then was unable to boot up again after a pod restart. What I ended up doing was deleting the postgresql PVC
column5: and reinstalling the helm chart again. I then did the system restore with a backup. This seemed to have worked. The postgresql database and artifactory seem to reboot fine from a short test we did tonight.

column1: Tl;dr: It looks good so far. The settings stayed after a few reboot reproduction attempts.

column2: We are not using the latest helm chart version though
column3: but that can be considered for a later time.

column1: Subject: [#184119] Member node not starting after Artifactory upgrade: Service registry ping failed
CAUTION EXTERNAL EMAIL: This email originated from outside of the organization. Do not click links or open attachments unless you recognize the sender and know the content is safe.
Thank you for joining the meeting with us on short notice.

column2: since the error "Error while trying to connect to local router at address 'http://localhost:8046/access':connection refused" is the only indication
column3: we suspected that the port 8046 is available for service but the service couldn't get to listen at the particular port which could have occurred due to existing old process IDs.

column2: we have decided to perform a clean restart of the service and observed the member node coming up after the restart. We were able to access the Artifactory member node.

we have observed the primary node is not available while we were troubleshooting the member node issue. You have checked with the team internally and confirmed that there were some changes done in regards to permissions on the primary node by the team. While trying to perform a restart of the primary node
column3: it returned a 'permission denied' error and from the artifactory-service.log
column4: we observed an 'access denied' error against a particular access-client library file.

column1: We have compared the permissions assigned to the files in specific between the working and the non-working instances and it appeared to be the same. As we couldn't get to the root cause of the issue on the primary node
column2: you have confirmed that you will get in touch with the team internally to verify the permissions.

column1: We would mark this support case as closed
column2: if any further assistance is needed in the future
column3: you may always reach out to JFrog Support. Thank you once again for your patience and understanding.

column2: I wonder why the storage watermark used the binary size (which is hypothetical) and not the artifact size (which is real).

column1: Artifact size never went above 1.5 GB throughout this month. The graph above from billing portal exactly reflected the binary size reported for each day. I hope the billing will be based on actual usage and not hypothetical usage.

column2: IN) <Raman.Divakaran@ust.com>; logand@jfrog.com

column1: EXTERNAL EMAIL - Do not click any links or open any attachments unless you trust the sender and know the content is safe.
The checksum based storage functions as a method of deduplication.

The binary size displayed is the storage occupied IF there was no deduplication. The artifact size is the true amount of storage occupied in the binarystore (the filesystem physically storing the artifacts).
So if you have a 100MB artifact in two repositories your binary size would show 200MB but since both repositories refer to the same artifact in the binarystore your artifact size is only 100MB.
Please feel free to let us know if there are any questions regarding this.

column1: Thank you for reaching out to JFrog Support.

column2: it could occur due to various reasons like missing sha1 value in the package.json file or the file might be duplicated/corrupted. And also It could be the reason that there is another NPM package with the same name/version but a different checksum than the one attempting to be installed

column1: A good way to verify if the binary file in Artifactory is corrupted or not is to manually download the npm file and compare its checksum with Artifactory.  You can run a "sha1sum" on the downloaded file and compare its output with the checksum of the NPM client and the checksum on Artifactory's UI for the particular package:
Example sha1sum for esutils-2.0.3.tgz  package is "74d2eb4de0b8da1293711910d50775b9b710ef64".
If it is happening for a particular package while pulling from the remote repository

column1: I have parsed over the given log file and could see the below errors related to the ‘security.import.xml” file.

Caused by: java.util.concurrent.ExecutionException: java.lang.IllegalArgumentException: An error has occurred while deserializing the file /opt/jfrog/artifactory/var/etc/artifactory/security.import.xml. Please assure it's validity or remove it from the 'etc' folder.

Caused by: java.lang.IllegalArgumentException: An error has occurred while deserializing the file /opt/jfrog/artifactory/var/etc/artifactory/security.import.xml. Please assure it's validity or remove it from the 'etc' folder.
Caused by: java.lang.IllegalStateException: Reading security data from backup of Artifactory version older than 1.2.5-rc6 is not supported!

column2: we could see that there is a file named security.import.xml in  /opt/jfrog/artifactory/var/etc/artifactory directory. During startup
column3: when there is a configuration file that includes the name ‘import’ tells Artifactory to override the current configuration file from the database. In order to overcome this issue
column4: I would request you to move this ‘security.import.xml’ file to a different location ( as a backup ) from the $JFROG_HOME/artifactory/var/etc/artifactory directory.  After making this change
column5: please ensure that all the microservices are down and then start the Artifatory application again.

02s6900002PAI67AAH5006900003jajQxAAIRe: [#184134] Xray Automatic master host selection for PostgresqlDear JFrog support team!
We have a JFrog Artifactory successfully connected to a Postgresql cloud cluster using Automatic master host selection feature in connect string: jdbc:postgresql://host1:6432
column2: host2:6432

column1: According to the Documentation for JFrog XRay https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Xray+System+YAMLIt is unclear how to connect the xray instance using the same mechanism.
We have 3 database servers: 1 master + 2 slaves. Failover may occur anytime at providers side. So we need always-working DB connection

The only connection string that works is: postgres://c-<cluster_id>.rw.mdb.yandexcloud.net:6432/xray?&targetServerType=master&ssl=true&sslrootcert=/opt/jfrog/xray/.postgresql/root.crt&sslmode=verify-full
But in this way we'll definitely have service disruption while database failover against DNS TTL + XRay's internal timers for resolving the database hostname.

column2: provide the JFrog engineer's way to use targetServerType feature.
Evgeny Litvinov

We're in the process of moving the Artifactory DB to new dedicated servers in the datacenter. I found that these problems correlate to periods of high load on the DB servers caused by other applications. The load isn't remarkably high
column2: but it's possible that we've hit some other bottlenck in the network or IO that caused this. We will move Artifactory to dedicated servers and hope that this solves our problems.

2021-10-25T10:22:20.7302 (jfrt ] [ERROR] [ac3b7941la6e854f] [s.b.c.RemoteBinaryProvider:348] [art-exec-16 sharding-cluster-eventual-33.remote-33. secondary_nodel Unable to execute ping request to Remote endpoint at http://localhost:8046/artifactory/binarystore : 503: Service Unavailable

2021-10-25T10:22:40.7312 (jfrt ] [ERROR] [fcb463e877f29e9] [s.b.c.RemoteBinaryProvider:348] [art-exec-15 sharding-cluster-eventual-s3.remote-s3.secondary_nodel Unable to execute ping request to Remote endpoint at http://localhost:8046/artifactory/binarystore : 503: Service Unavailable
The error usually occurs when the primary node tries contacting the member node s3 to make a connection
column2: however
column3: it might not establish a connection at that point of time where the member node is still booting up or unresponsive due to the heavy loads or something else. You need to check the resource monitoring graph of CPU/JVM Memory/Thread/DB pool status at that time for secondary_nodel instance. As you are aware this error will not cause any issue. Hence you may safely ignore the error.

column1: 2021-10-22T07:10:22.410Z ^[[1;32m[jfrt ]^[[0;39m ^[[1;31m[ERROR]^[[0;39m [98faed96a8ecf039] [ShardingBinaryProviderImpl:351] [art-exec-226274     ] - Failed to stream binary to sub provider: java.io.IOException: No space left on device
java.util.concurrent.ExecutionException: java.io.IOException: No space left on device
Seems like a disk space issue or more specifically disk space which might be related to the _pre under the cache fs.

The cache-fs does not include files that are in progress of being uploaded which are saved under cache/_pre. Thus it is recommended to keep extra spaces for _pre folder<https://nam11.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.jfrog.com%2Fjira%2Fbrowse%2FRTFACT-14606&data=04%7C01%7Csjing%40paypal.com%7Cf4cbcff036ca4ed66e1008d997b181e9%7Cfb00791460204374977e21bac5f3f4c8%7C0%7C0%7C637707610915590158%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&sdata=ubdgqtzrYYQENpzBQcz6Mqrd6wJYawf3Pwh6rLl%2B3%2FE%3D&reserved=0>.

column1: Right now you have 100 GB of cache-fs
column2: do you see it constantly full? If yes
column3: we should consider increasing it - On a high scale
column4: if the cache-fs is too low in size
column5: it will be busier with rotating than actually serving from the cache
column6: so a bigger cache can help improve the performance of download requests and thus also reduce the requests done against the S3.

column2: since you are an E+ customer there are more tuning that you can do to reduce the load from the server
column3: but it will require some additional modifications to the binarystore.xml and further testings.

column1: The one I particularly recommend (and it's not a complicated change) is the direct cloud storage download.

column2: Artifactory upon download request will redirect the client to download the file directly from the S3 and you can configure this for specific repositories and for a specific size of files (e.g file size which is larger than 20 MB).

column1: The main advantage of such a method is that it reduces the load from the Artifactory since it's moving the load to the client.

column2: usually
column3: Amazon machines have a network bandwidth limit
column4: but there is no limit when downloading from the S3 directly
column5: so you are not limited by it with this method.

column1: There is also a feature called direct upload where we remove the eventual and uploads will be uploaded directly to the S3 which is called direct upload (eventual-less)
column2: however
column3: this will require you to change the binarystore.xml entirely and will require additional tests before implementing it but for now
column4: it should be easier to implement the first method while both can help.

Thank you for confirming the use case.
I believe the user-group association is working with the UI. However
column2: you are facing the issue whenever you are trying to resolve the packages from Jenkins.

column1: This is a known issue as described in this JIRA (RTFACT-14466) that the user group association for the SAML users are not persistent and it will be persistent only specific to UI session. As soon as you log out of the UI session
column2: the association will be lost. That is the reason why it is not working when you are trying to resolve the package from the Jenkins it is not working as it is losing the user and group association.

column1: In order to get rid of this issue
column2: we have introduced the feature called SCIM which is described in this link - https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/SCIM#SCIM-AzureADAzureAD. However
column3: please be informed that for this
column4: it is required to have the "Security Pack" subscription. I have included your account manager in case you do not have that subscription and would like to have it.

column1: Thank you for reaching out to us.
Since the index.yaml file and the actual charts are located in different hosts/path the configuration of the Helm remote repository needs to be as follows:
The repository URL should point to the root path where the index.yaml is found - "https://helm.datadoghq.com"
The  "Chart Base URL" should point to the path where the charts are stored - "https://github.com/DataDog/helm-charts/releases/download/"
I tested on my end and verified that I was able to proxy the Datadog Helm repo and the charts are cached in Artifactory.
Please find below screenshot of the remote repository configuration I used:
Make sure to aggregate the remote repository in a virtual repo (in order to properly resolve charts
column2: virtual repository is required) and to update the client (helm repo update) before trying to resolve the charts.

column1: 02s6900002PAJbkAAH5006900003jai4kAAA[#184068] Docker Login - Auth Header goes missingHi Chris
Thank you for reaching out to us.

column2: the flow of a docker login is as follows:

column1: 1) First the client will send a '/v2' request without any credentials which should indeed result with the 401.

column2: the registry (Artifactory) should also send a response header 'WWW-authenticate' with a Bearer realm that the client will use for authentication.

column1: 2) The next request should be 'api/docker/null/v2/token' if you are using the repository path or 'api/docker/<REPO_NAME>/v2/token' if you are using the subdomain/port method for docker. The client should send parameters in the URL. For example when I login with a user 'user1'
column2: the following is sent:

column1: The 'account' is the username that is used in the docker login command and the 'service' is the host returned in the 'WWW-authenticate' header of the previous request.
A header 'Authorization Basic ..' should also be sent by the client for this request.
3) The client should now issue a request for '/v2' with a granted token 'Authorization: Bearer <token>'.
The non_authneticated_user 401 response from Artifactory is expected and is used to determine the Bearer realm
column2: it should not affect the auth header not sent by the client.

column1: As per my understanding you already found that in stage (2) the request is sent without auth. I advise to check the first '/v2' request and catch the outgoing headers and response as well.

column2: it is possible that the auth is stripped by the proxy/ALB.

column1: Let me know if I can further assist.

column1: Subject: [#180835] Nuget timeouts and Artifactory not serving from cache
I have checked and discussed the issue internally
column2: as per functionality of Nuget Repository
column3: Artifactory looks for available versions of packages that have been requested. So it goes to upstream i.e. nuget.org<https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fnuget.org%2F&data=04%7C01%7CStephen.OBrien%40chrobinson.com%7Ce6a74b60e6bc498a52ed08d9945bce54%7Cd441ad83623546d6ab1a89744a91b1d8%7C1%7C0%7C637703944300857248%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&sdata=KaJqpxxRRhjnz2uF5snJ9A6u6P7f1XBEJBIVkkr3VcM%3D&reserved=0> to resolve the package
column4: so even if you have a package that is available on Remote Repository cache when a request has been made it goes to upstream before resolving the package from Remote Repository Cache.

column1: I have done a lot of research on the scenario and found we have a JIRA opened RTMID-20557 (This is an Internal JIRA
column2: so it won't be accessible from outside).

column1: R&D is working on bringing the changes so Nuget Repository will resolve the packages from Nuget Repository cache also if nuget.org<https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fnuget.org%2F&data=04%7C01%7CStephen.OBrien%40chrobinson.com%7Ce6a74b60e6bc498a52ed08d9945bce54%7Cd441ad83623546d6ab1a89744a91b1d8%7C1%7C0%7C637703944300867208%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&sdata=G8i%2BeoLkWOLU7kGQKoNWe24YZWmhAhfiPfbf9va7eiA%3D&reserved=0> is not accessible.

column2: I noticed this behaviourWhen I have a correct feed defined in my Nuget.config
column3: the dotnet restore can restore the package. config : <add key="ArtDevV3" value="https://artifactory.group.euroclear.com:15443/artifactory/api/nuget/v3/eoc-nuget-dev" protocolVersion="3" />When I have an incorrect package.config (missing protocolVersion="3") I have the same message as in the pipeline. config: <add key="ArtDevV3Bad" value="https://artifactory.group.euroclear.com:15443/artifactory/api/nuget/v3/eoc-nuget-dev" /> So I started the CI pipeline again
column4: cancelled it during the restore to get the temporary nuget config generated by the CLI and noticed the feed is also missing protocolVersion="3".

column1: In the CI pipeline restore step
column2: I also experimented overriding the config by adding the argument '--configfile ../nuget.config'
column3: pointing to a nuget.config with correct V3 protocol settings
column4: and this time the temp nuget.config was not generated/used and the restore was done successfully.

column1: I referred already to the similar case we raised
column3: where unfortunately we missed somehow in the validation if the issue was resolved.

column1: The issue is not noticed as long as the nuget packages to be restored are not SemVerLevel 2 versioned packages. eg. Nuget.Frameworks 5.0.0 and 5.5.0 are SemVerLevel 2

column1: I also noticed that when using a correct nuget.config V3
column2: the communition with Artifactory is using a webrequest like (SUCCESS): GET https://artifactory.group.euroclear.com:15443/artifactory/api/nuget/v3/eoc-nuget-dev/registration-semver2/nuget.frameworks/index.json

column2: Nanda

column1: Thank you for contacting JFrog Support.

column2: I will assume that you mean for authentication using a user’s API key and not an access token (kindly let me know if you mean otherwise.

column1: Authenticating LDAP users using the user’s API key is possible only if the “Auto Create Users) is enabled in the LDAP settings. The API key is saved under the internal user entity in Artifactory
column2: so the user must exist in Artifactory and not only in the LDAP server for this to work. The user also must be placed under a specific group.

column1: Please note that API key authentication will work only for REST API/JFrog CLI calls and not for UI authentication.

02s6900002PAK8UAAX5006900003YfNu2AAF[#182706] Access Federation from external Mission Control IssuesHi Hap and team
Thanks for meeting with me yesterday.
On the call we were troubleshooting the Access Federation issues on the AWS environments.
At the beginning of the call
column2: we saw that full-broadcast from US to EU is working
column3: while any live events are not getting synced.

column2: we suspected that there is inconsistency in the syncs between EU to US
column3: where it felt as it's partially working.

column1: We were able to resolve the live sync from US to EU by restarting the US cluster nodes.
I have informed you that it is crucial to restart the nodes of a cluster after an Access import.
It is a known behaviour for JFrog that after access import
column2: a restart is required for Access Federation to work. In case this step was not shared with you in the past

column1: It is also mentioned as the final step in this knowledge base article.
I have reviewed the Support bundle from the US cluster
column2: and from the logs I can confirm there was no restart of the US nodes since "2021-10-19T18:39:25.273Z" on node "ip-10-213-15-156.ec2.internal" and "2021-10-19T18:41:40.622Z" on node "ip-10-213-14-22.ec2.internal".

column1: This is while I believe the access import was on "2021-10-19T19:45"
column2: a bit later. I can see in the logs you ran the full_broadcast
column4: a restart is missing.

column1: I am confident that the lack of restart
column2: which I can confirm from the logs
column3: is the reason Access Federation wasn't syncing live events.

column1: With regards to the partial sync issues from EU to US
column2: we confirmed these were due to group dependency missing on some users and such. A full broadcast resolved these.

column1: With regards to the REALM not updating as part of the full broadcast
column2: I informed you that this is most likely due to the "modified" timestamp of the user entity being unmodified.

column1: When the target Access server receives the users with the modified REALM
column2: it checks for the modified timestamp. It will accept the change only when the modified timestamp is newer. This is why applying any other change on the users does trigger that sync.
you will also update the modified date upon changing the REALM
column3: and will let us know if this resolves this problem.

column1: Waiting forward to hearing from you today.

column5: we enabled the http port by updating the values.yaml and when we hit the the LB URL
column6: the request forwarded to Artifactory as expected.

column1: Hope you folks are doing good. Please find responses to your questions below:
Question 1): Can we go ahead and upgrade directly to the latest release? Version 7.27.3?
JFrog Support): If you have recently upgraded to Artifactory version 6.23.31 we would recommend that you upgrade to version 7.21.3 and then plan for the latest version.
Question 2): Are the hardware requirements cumulative? Artifactory required cores + Mission Control required cores + Xray required cores + etc.
JFrog Support): From JFrog Artifactory version 7.27.3
column2: Mission Control has been integrated directly into Artifactory as a service. You no longer need to install Mission Control to use the features it provides. You must enable the service in Artifactory through the Artifactory system YAML file. For more information
for Artifactory and Xray it is recommended to use a dedicated server
column3: best is to refer to System Requirements for information on requirements.

column1: Question 3): Docs say AJP connector is unsupported but not how to fix it
column2: how do we fix it?

column1: JFrog Support): AJP Connector has been removed and will no longer work
column2: HTTP should be used as an alternative. You can also refer to Release Notes for countering this breaking change.

column1: Question 4): Our current DB is db.m5.8xlarge I could see no recommendation for DB changes when upgrading to Artifactory 7. Is there a recommended hardware bump? We are also running Postgresql v10.17 on an external DB

JFrog Support): There is no such hardware recommendation for DB however for Artifactory 7.x to run with PostgreSQL you must create a dedicated PostgreSQL database instance and then configure Artifactory to use it as described on this confluence page.
JFrog Support): If rolling back an Artifactory upgrade is necessary
column2: you'll need to reinstall an older version of Artifactory and load a database backup. Here is a knowledge base article for reference.

column2: we could infer that the Xray DB sync and the scans were working as expected and suddenly started failing with the above errors. The pattern appears in a way that the Xray service was able to serve the requests as expected for quite some time and it abruptly started to fail the requests. We have observer a similar pattern of error in the past due to resource issues and DB issues. We would request you to share with us how the database was installed and if there are any errors logged on the same. Can you confirm if the database is a single node or if it's a cluster?
it appears that the group cloudbees_cds_team_admins is assigned with the Project Admins role. Can you tell if this group currently has any members? If it does
column3: when you log in with one of the group members
column4: are you able to perform any tasks within the CDS-Team project such as creating roles
column5: adding other members to the project etc?

column2: it means that the group was assigned with the proper permissions for this project.
it is worth checking the group to see if the members are being added to it when they log in for the first time. In order to do so
column3: please navigate to the Administration tab >> Identity and Access >> Groups and verify the group members.

Thank you for contacting JFrog Support.
I have thoroughly inspected the Artifactory and Xray Support Bundles you shared with me and was able to find the following requests to Xray’s ‘/api/v1/summary/artifact’:

column2: please notice that these requests do not appear to be sent to Artifactory
column3: meaning that they are handled completely by Xray.

column1: According to the right-most column of the above requests
column2: it takes Xray about 12
column4: 000 milliseconds (12-15 seconds) to respond to the API call
column5: which makes me wonder why it takes another ~50 seconds for the response to arrive at the cURL client.

column2: Xray’s default log verbosity does not provide any additional information about this specific API call. However
column3: we can take the following steps to gather more information:

column1: 1. Execute the same cURL command to the internal Xray address (http://localhost:8000/api/v1/summary/artifact)
column2: bypassing the reverse proxy. This will help us understand if the slowness is related to the reverse proxy.

column1: 2. Increase the log verbosity and reproduce the issue:

column2: locate a file called “server_log4go_config.xml”

column1: B: Change ‘<level>INFO</level>’ to: ‘<level>DEBUG</level>’ and save the file (no need to restart)
C: Execute the cURL command once more
D: Provide me with a copy of Xray’s ‘request.log’ and most importantly ‘xray_server.log’
I am looking forward to hearing from you.

column2: I suggest the following procedure: disable the encryption on the source instance. Therefore please follow these steps in order to perform the import/export:

Perform the import  on the new instance
Reactivate encryption on the source instance

column1: We need to make sure that the Artifactory and Bamboo servers are in the same time zone. Artifactory will be in the UTC time zone

column1: A brief description of the master key is as follows:
The master.key is used to securely synchronize files between cluster nodes. It is responsible for encrypting and decrypting the shared data in the database.\

column3: resulting in all data being encrypted by this master key.

column1: 02s6900002PALrBAAX5006900003jaQJxAAMRe: [#183718] Fwd: Configure JFrog Artifactory SSOHi Ayelet
Thank you for joining today's meeting with me!

column2: we saw a few parameters that I recommended modifying:

column1: 1. Identifier (Entity ID) - The Identifier should be similar to "Azure AD Identifier" mentioned in the 4th section "Set up artifactory". For example: https://sts.windows.net/7000bebb-3941-4379-8b48-7fcdf8e85f3e/
2. Sign on URL - This parameter should have the same value of the Artifactory URL
column2: as follows: https://$SERVER_NAME.jfrog.io

column1: After modifying the Azure Enterprise Application
column2: we'll need to modify the "SAML Service Provider Name" on the Artifactory side to have the exact value of the "Identifier (Entity ID)" on the Azure AD side.
you will need to add the "user.groups" claim under the 2nd section "User Attributes & Claims". In my case
column3: the group claim was configured as follows:

column2: you will need to manually create the Azure groups and name them according to the Object ID of the group and grant the required permissions:

column1: Once a SAML user that's associated with this group will login to the Artifactory instance
column2: the SAML authentication will occur on the Azure AD side and in correspondence
column3: it will pass the groups association of the user in the SAML XML response.

column2: you will need to add the URLs of the Groups and Emails in the Artifactory side
column3: which can be retrieved from the "User Attributes & Claims" under Azure:

column1: As we were discussing the SCIM feature
column2: you may want to consider implementing it instead of the SAML SSO integration
column3: as it will have several major advantages:

column1: 1. User/Group persistence - SAML SSO users are only persistent for the UI Session
column2: therefore
column3: their permissions and group associations will not be valid outside the UI session. This will not allow SAML users to authenticate against Artifactory when configuring the clients (NPM/Maven/Docker/etc) without generating an Access Token for each user.

column1: SCIM will manage both users and groups by provisioning them and creating them on the Artifactory side. Artifactory will treat these users the same way it will for internal users
column2: which will let the users configure their clients without encountering any permission issues.

column1: 2. Management on Azure AD - While SAML SSO requires the administrator to create the users/groups both in Artifactory and Azure AD. The SCIM feature provisioning will aggregate all the new changes
column2: therefore
column3: the management of your users and groups can be handled only on the Azure AD side
column4: without tinkering with the configurations on the Artifactory side.

column2: you may take a look at this SCIM Wiki page.

column1: As for configuring the Azure AD provisioning
column2: please follow this guide from the official Microsoft documentation.

column1: In case reconfiguring the SAML SSO parameters on both the Artifactory and Azure AD still cause an error
column2: please click here to book a session with me go over the configuration live during our meeting.

column1: We will need an Azure AD administrator present in this session
column2: in order to apply all changes on the fly.

column1: Let me know if any additional clarifications are needed.

column1: 02s6900002PALuaAAH5006900003YeigMAARRe: [#182288] Duplicate repositories however 1 has permission issueHi Sophie
column2: There is no reason to set Include Patterns if you are using the default all (**/*). It's more efficient to add an Include Pattern for what you want then
column3: an Exclude Pattern for what you don't. This way your Include Pattern only allows access to what you want and in turn excludes everything else. You can see how this becomes very efficient when pulling from a repository the likes of github.com where there are thousands of projects to pull from.

column2: both the github-release-remote and test-github have the same Include and Exclude Patterns however
column3: I am unable to download from github-release-remote the draw.io-15.3.8-windows-installer.exe file after adding jgraph/drawio-desktop/**/* within the Include Pattern. Although
column4: I can download the file from test-github.

column1: NOTE: Things can still be downloaded from github-release-remote just not anything within the jgraph/drawio-desktop/**/* path.

column2: I'll do the following additional testing:Download something else from both repositories that exist in the cache and that doesn't. To verify artifacts can be pulled locally (cache) and externally (proxy) by both repositories.Add additional Include Patterns and attempt to download artifacts from them. To verify adding new Include Patterns are working for both repositories.

column1: 02s6900002PAMASAA55006900003YeM6nAAFRe: [#181908] Limitation when searching for packagesHey Daniel
Thanks for the update. The issue re-appeared this morning and I followed your suggestion and did a tcpdump while attempting to login.
I used the “any” interface just to make sure I have all the data. As mentioned before
column2: our Artifactory is running as a docker container in a docker network. The gateway is 192.168.14.1
column3: the PostgresDB is 192.168.14.2 and Artifactory is running at 192.168.14.3. NGINX is running natively on the docker host to proxy requests. The same docker host is also running Jenkins.

column1: When I filter the pcap file on HTTP protocol (see tcpdump any-failure http.png) you can see the POST (clicking the login button) and getting a 401 error 20sec later. In between there is a lot of PGSQL traffic between the DB and Artifactory.
Filtering the same file on LDAP protocol (see tcpdump any-failure ldap.png) shows no results. Indicating there was no request and obviously also no response.

After the capture I restarted the container and the login took a very long time. Looking at the PCAP the login request was made at t+10 and acknowledged t+90. (See tcpdump any-working http post.png and tcpdump any-working http 200.png). Filtering the file on LDAP it shows several successful ldap searches  (see tcpdump any-working ldap.png) so I’m not sure as to why it takes 80sec (4x 20?) before the login comes through.
Because of security I cannot provide you the pcap files.
I did not upload a new support bundle since I believe it will not show any additional info. Let me know if you disagree and I’ll upload a new zip.
Hope this information is of any use.
Thank you for your patience while I was reviewing the new log files.

column2: I wasn’t able to find any new information regarding the timeout issues you encounter.

column1: It appears that the request is being sent from Artifactory to the LDAP server but the response is not returned which is resulting with the timeout error.
As a next step I recommend tracing or pinging the connection between Artifactory and the LDAP server when the error occurs to further investigate where the connection issue may reside.

column2: I am also trying to set up a similar environment to reproduce the error internally.

column1: Thank you for reaching out to us.
Since the index.yaml file and the actual charts are located in different hosts/path the configuration of the Helm remote repository needs to be as follows:
The repository URL should point to the root path where the index.yaml is found - "https://helm.datadoghq.com<https://protect-us.mimecast.com/s/RT8uCDkrmYiQkoZ1IWBEsC?domain=helm.datadoghq.com>"

The  "Chart Base URL" should point to the path where the charts are stored - "https://github.com/DataDog/helm-charts/releases/download/<https://protect-us.mimecast.com/s/lGFGCERvnZtKNljmuwX_b-?domain=github.com>"
I tested on my end and verified that I was able to proxy the Datadog Helm repo and the charts are cached in Artifactory.
Please find below screenshot of the remote repository configuration I used:
Make sure to aggregate the remote repository in a virtual repo (in order to properly resolve charts
column2: virtual repository is required) and to update the client (helm repo update) before trying to resolve the charts.

column1: Let me know if the above configuration works on your end
column2: I look forward to your update.

column1: Cc: Rishav Choudhary <rishav.choudhary@infosys.com>; Ashok Gedela <ashok.gedela@infosys.com>; AlokSingh Rathore <aloksingh.rathore@infosys.com>; Jordan Severance <jordan.severance@infosys.com>; sidheshi@jfrog.com
Subject: [#183990] Need only 443 port for JFrog NLB
Thank you for joining the session with us today.

column2: you explained to us by default the NLB is using both 80 and 443 ports as a listener. Due to security reasons
column3: you have to use only 443 port and as suggested
column4: you have disabled port 80 at the load balancer level by updating the active listeners on the NLB by removing port 80 on the load balancer configuration. We reproduced the issue by hitting the load balancer URL where the URL failed to forward the request to Artifactory.  We modified the values.yaml config file to have the https backend traffic and we made sure to have the https port enabled then performed the helm upgrade and still the issue persisted. As a test
column5: we enabled the http port by updating the values.yaml and when we hit the the LB URL
column6: the request forwarded to Artifactory as expected.

column2: we will further check with our internal team on the reported issue and we will keep you posted with findings.

stash-core" is private

column2: currently there’s no ETA on when this functionality will be implemented. Therefore
column3: if you would like to continue to use the Jenkins plugin
column4: the way to implement this now with Projects is via the following steps:

column1: Publish the build normally to artifactory-build-info (the default repository where all build info has been stored until now).
Use the API to retrieve this build information and publish it to the appropriate project’s build info
Delete the existing build info JSON in artifactory-build-info

column2: artifactory-build-info is the default repository where all build information is published when a Project isn't specified. If a build is published to a Project
column3: the build-info will be located in a repository with the following name: <project-key>-build-info.

column2: you can restructure the pipeline to use the JFrog CLI or API which both support the Project option.

Thank you for the answer. I asked my team if anyone has made any changes to the Config Descriptor via the UI but I doubt that's the case as that's not usually our practice. What are other possible causes of this issue?

Please note that I didn't simply rename the "artifactory.config.latest.xml" file. That file also had invalid config. I had to manually edit the config before naming it "artifactory.config.import.xml". I only knew the correct value to add because I contacted a colleague who knew what it was supposed to be. When the config descriptor gets corrupted does the "artifactory.config.latest.xml" file usually contain a correct version? Is it unusual that in this case it was corrupted too?

column2: Maria (Application Infrastructure) <Maria.Koleva@morganstanley.com>

column1: Subject: [#184009] Artifactory not starting up - config error in logs
Thank you for contacting JFrog Support.
From the error messages and the steps you have taken to restore Artifactory
column2: it does look like the <repoKey> missing in the config descriptor has caused an issue.

column1: It's hard to determine why the "repoKey" was removed
column2: but the possibility is that it was removed from the UI under the Admin module - Advanced | Config Descriptor page.

column1: In case of a corrupted config descriptor issue
column2: the best way would be to restore the previous working config descriptor
column3: which you have followed to change the name of the "artifactory.config.latest.xml" file to "artifactory.config.import.xml" file and restart Artifactory. (https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Configuration+Files)

column1: The recommended way to prevent it from happening again would be to keep a backup of Artifactory<https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Backups>.

column1: Thank you for reaching out to us.
Since the index.yaml file and the actual charts are located in different hosts/path the configuration of the Helm remote repository needs to be as follows:
The repository URL should point to the root path where the index.yaml is found - "https://helm.datadoghq.com<https://protect-us.mimecast.com/s/RT8uCDkrmYiQkoZ1IWBEsC?domain=helm.datadoghq.com>"

The  "Chart Base URL" should point to the path where the charts are stored - "https://github.com/DataDog/helm-charts/releases/download/<https://protect-us.mimecast.com/s/lGFGCERvnZtKNljmuwX_b-?domain=github.com>"
I tested on my end and verified that I was able to proxy the Datadog Helm repo and the charts are cached in Artifactory.
Please find below screenshot of the remote repository configuration I used:
Make sure to aggregate the remote repository in a virtual repo (in order to properly resolve charts
column2: virtual repository is required) and to update the client (helm repo update) before trying to resolve the charts.

column1: Let me know if the above configuration works on your end
column2: I look forward to your update.

column1: Thank you for joining us on the call. We were able to troubleshoot the issue with the maven virtual repository unable to list the repository contents. On checking the errors we could see that the issue was due to trying to fetch from another bucket: fabric-artifacts. We checked and found that this belonged to the repository s3.amazonaws.com. We then removed this repository from the virtual and then we could see that the content was showing fine. We then checked the URL of this repo and could see that it was not valid and that was causing the issue

column2: we investigated another build that was failing to publish packages to the snapshots repository. We could see that it was failing due to the snapshot handling policy. We then enabled handle releases in the repository configuration and could see that the package was deployed successfully and the build also succeeded. So in general
column4: Artifactory allows you to deploy release artifacts into this repository. If Handle Snapshots is set
column5: Artifactory allows you to deploy snapshot artifacts into this repository. In our case
column6: the Handle release was not set so that would mean that any artifact deployed to this repository should have the word SNAPSHOT in it to be considered as a snapshot artifact.

column1: Please keep us posted on the other build failure and if you still see the issue
column2: we will wait to hear back from you.

column1: 02s6900002PANDNAA55006900003YgNZTAA3Re: [#183550] Unable to access the JFrog Artifactory V7 Web Management Portal after integrating with AWS Postgresql/Aurora RDS datastoreHi Venu

Things appear to be working now for the happy day scenario of connecting a fresh new Artifactory Version 7 AWS EC2 based instance to a newly created AWS RDS Aurora/Postgres v11.8 instance when using the AWS Cloud Formation automation for the very first time..

column2: I am seeing two out-of-the-ordinary
column3: unaccounted for and not understood issues arise when I use the AWS Cloud Formation automation a second time to recreate a new AWS EC2 based Artifactory Version 7 instance to connect to an already existing AWS RDS Aurora/Postgres v11.8 instance that has been previously pre-populated with the Artifactory database objects (i.e. tables and configuration items/attributes).

column1: The newly instantiated AWS EC2 Artifactory Version 7 instance appears to successfully starts up the middleware and connects to the AWS RDS Aurora/Postgres v11.8 instance to retrieve the necessary configuration attributes that were previously populated. HOWEVER
column2: NO NEW "artifactory.config.latest.xml" CONFIGURATION IS CREATED AT START UP YET THE MIDDLEWARE APPEARS TO START UP AND WORK AS FAR AS I CAN TELL. WE NEED TO UNDERSTAND WHAT IS HAPPENING AND WHY FROM AN ARTIFACTORY CONFIGURATION STATE PERSPECTIVE AND DATABASE MANAGMENT PERSPECTIVE.As part of our AWS Cloud Formation automation implementation
column3: we copy the "artifactory.config.latest.xml" to file "artifactory.config.import.xml" and manipulate the "reverseProxy" XML attribute from "path" to "subDomain" to support that Docker Registry access method and place it in the /opt/jfrog/artifactory/var/etc/artifactory directory. THE "artifactory.config.latest.xml" FILE DOES SHOW UP ON OUR VERY FIRST RUN OF THE AWS CLOUD FORMATION TO CREATE THE AWS EC2 ARTIFACTORY VERSION 7 INSTANCE
column4: HOWEVER THE "artifactory.config.import.xml" IS NOT BEING PICKED UP BY THE ALREADY RUNNING ARTIFACTORY JVM PROCESS. I HAVE TO RESTART ARTIFACTORY WITHIN THE CLOUD FORMATION AUTOMATION TO GENERATE THE NEW BOOTSTRAP FILE. WE NEED TO UNDERSTAND WHY THIS IS THE CASE.

column1: I WOULD LIKE TO SET UP ANOTHER ONLINE INTERACTIVE ZOOM TROUBLESHOOTING SESSION ASAP TO REVIEW AND UNDERSTAND THESE PARTICULAR ISSUES AND FIND POTENTIAL REMEDIES.

Could you kindly confirm if the anonymous user has permission to the local-npm-repl repository? It does not
column2: we require the user to authenticate to pull artifacts from npm-local-repl repository. Users have to be members of the read-and-write group to access this repo. The anonymous user is not a member of this group.Additionally
column3: could you kindly share with me the content of the "Any Remote" permission content of the Anonymous user? (under Administration -> Identity and Access -> Users -> anonymous -> Repositories -> click on the "Any Remote" permission)The npm-local-repl repo is not included in the "Any Remote" permission. The only repos assigned to this permission are 3rd party registries (e.g.
column4: https://registry.npmjs.org as npm-remote). The anonymous user has access to these repos because the anonymous user is a member of the readers group. The readers group is assigned permissions to the Any Remote permission.

column1: 02s6900002PANQHAA55006900003jano8AAARe: [#184207] Request for help improving setup after downtime incidentHi support team
Today morning we had an incident caused by Artifactory downtime. We run artifactory in kubernetes using the artifactory-ha helm chart
column2: with mission control and xray next to it.

column1: We are hoping you can review our setup
column2: and the issues we had this morning
column3: to help us improve our setup.

column1: Reason for downtime: We have regular cluster patches which do node by node restarts. Today it happened that our primary & member-0 pods were on the same node and went down simultaneously. All the load then befell on member-1 (the last node). When the primary tried to restart
column2: it could not connect to member-1 (timeouts due to the high load)
column3: which prevented it from starting up healthily.This in turn caused member-0 to not start up healthily
column4: as it required primary to be available first.

column1: Eventually member-1 was also killed with the patching and artifactory was down
column2: at which point the load of multiple clusters restarting was too much for artifactory to start back up. Communication between the pods was not possible due to timeouts due to high CPU load.
we noticed that out of the two member nodes handling traffic
column3: one was fully capped out on CPU
column4: while the other was only using 25% of the limits.

column1: Questions:Do you have examples for using node anti-affinity to ensure primary & member pods don't run on the same node?Why do we see such different usage between the two member nodes?Do you have more tips on the kubernetes setup
column2: to prevent our clusters from DDoSing ourselves?We noticed the default cache_fs location goes to /var/opt/jfrog/... - which is not in the PVC
column3: nor in an emptydir of sorts
column4: so it ends up on the node's storage. Are you aware of this
column5: and if so do you have workarounds to make sure the cache is stored on a PVC?When restarts happen
column6: is there a specific order that the pods should be restarting in
column8: a recent artifactory update lists that primary node should no longer be necessary. Are there plans to update the helm chart with that new setup?

column2: we would like to quickly make improvements to prevent future incidents like this
column3: and this is high priority for us.

column2: Jeroen

column1: 02s6900002PANcmAAH5006900003jaVk0AAE[#183868] Unable to upgrade Artifactory from 7.17.11 to 7.27.6.Hi team
Thank you for joining the call today.
Over the call we talked about the JIRA that was raised in order to handle the failing DB migrations where ‘sql_require_primary_key’ is enabled on MySQL database.
I mentioned that this JIRA was acknowledged by R&D and is pending code review.
We have performed the suggested workaround which involves these steps:
1. Shutdown the failed node service (which was tried for upgrade).
2. Create the access_db_check table with primary key as below:
3. Verified the schema status by running this SQL query:
4. Updated the access_schema_version table using below query to make this migration successful.
update access_schema_version set success=1 where script='V7_25__DbCheck.sql';
5. Restart the service to proceed with remaining migrations.

column2: we noticed that Artifactory was running successfully.

column1: We then moved on to upgrade all the remaining nodes one by one.

column2: we talked about the best approach to upgrade a large HA environment
column3: as you noticed that when the nodes are in different versions
column4: the UI is stuck.

column1: I recommended removing each node from the Load Balancer before upgrading it and bringing it back to the Load Balancer afterwards. You mentioned that you would rather take out 50% of the nodes
column2: upgrade them and then bring them back to the Load Balancer and repeat the process for the remaining 50%.

column1: Should you have any additional questions regarding what we have covered during the call
column2: please feel free to ask. We will keep this ticket open for a few more days.

column1: Thank you again for your time today. It has been a pleasure meeting with you.

column1: 02s6900002PANWkAAP5006900003MmUuLAAV[#177454] Not able to push docker images to artifactoryHi Sintarose
I wanted to start off by saying thanks for the response back to my last email. With that said
column2: the reason why I don’t think your Production HAProxy configuration is the correct one is that there are no rewrite rules to handle the incoming docker request for docker repositories.

column1: If you look at this example and compare it to your current Production configuration you can see that you need at least one rewrite rule to handle the versioning of the docker request:
redirect scheme https code 301 if !{ ssl_fc }
# Don't need stickiness if there's only one server
reqirep ^([^\ :]*)\ /v2(.*$) \1\ /artifactory/api/docker/docker-your-repo/v2\2 --this rewrite adds v2 to uri
Would you please let me know your thoughts?

column2: I was able to identify that we have a known bug titled "Issues with loading plugins using the Kubernetes secrets" tracked under internal INST-2995 with no ETA at this point.

column1: Option 1: Possible workaround is to manually delete the files under /artifactory_bootstrap/plugins and /opt/jfrog/artifactory/var/etc/artifactory/plugins directories at first and then update the secrets and perform the helm upgrade.
Option 2: Manually edit the artifactCleanup.json file in /opt/jfrog/artifactory/var/etc/artifactory/plugins with latest changes and reload the plugin.
Could you please perform the above workaround and advise if you were able to trigger the plugin and advise if you were able to trigger the plugins manually.
I look forward to your feedback.

column1: Thank you for contacting JFrog Support.

column2: please see my answers below

column1: We currently have an Artifactory instance with 40TB of artifacts. Is there a way to distribute the artifacts through the shards to more evenly distribute the data across the shards. I can only find this is as artifacts are written.
There are 3 options you can implement with sharding "writeBehavior" settings.
roundRobin (default): Binaries are written to each mount using a round robin strategy.
freeSpace: Binaries are written to the mount with the greatest absolute volume of free space available.
percentageFreeSpace: Binaries are written to the mount with the percentage of free space available.
Our current Artifactory cluster file system has the following directories on the existing cluster: archive
column2: ha-backup
column4: ha-etc. Should I point the existing cluster to ha-data/filestore?

column1: With your filestore configuration (using ha-data and ha-backup)
column2: it seems like you're using NFS mount. You may migrate your filestore to the local filestore location following the instruction from our wiki page. If this is not the case
column3: please share your current filestore settings (including binarystore.xml file under $ARTIFACTORY_HOME/etc/) and how you would like to proceed with filestore settings.

column1: Is there a performance difference using sharding vs. our existing single Artifactory cluster file system (all are mounted on a NetApp device)
Unmatched stability and reliability: Thanks to redundant storage of binaries
column2: the system can withstand any mount going down as long as M >= R.

column1: Unlimited scalability: If the underlying storage available approaches depletion
column2: you only need to add another mount; a process that requires no downtime of the filestore. Once the mount is up and running
column3: the system regenerates the filestore redundancy according to configuration parameters you control.

column1: Filestore performance optimization: Sharding Binary Provider offers several configuration parameters that allow you to optimize how binaries are read from or written to the filestore according to your specific system’s requirements.
I hope this answers your questions. Please let me know if you have further questions about this case and I will be glad to assist you.

02s6900002PANo9AAH5006900003YgEPxAAN[#183320] Propagation is not allowed while current member is not boundHi Alex
I've been looking through this case for a bit today
column2: it's strange as this isn't an error we've seen before so I'm checking the code to see where the error gets thrown. There isn't much information there though
column3: so I looked into your other tickets to gather some more logs of the event and saw that 183025 had a support bundle from a9y-master-c from Oct 18-19. I wanted to check that node out specifically since you mentioned restarting it seemed to fix issues on your end. Looking at the bundle I found the propagation errors seemed to coincide with errors in the Access service
column4: and checking those out I saw

column1: Caused by: java.lang.OutOfMemoryError: unable to create native thread: possibly out of memory or process/resource limits reached
which is strange as I see
which should be more than enough. Where this error is coming from is the fact that there are 31.7k threads in the thread dump for a9y-master-c
column2: it would seem like something is stuck there but there are no blocked threads. Rather it seems most of the threads are in a simple waiting state and are delayed or put on hold by the scheduler.

column1: HikariCP Main housekeeper Id=37 in TIMED_WAITING on lock=java.util.concurrent.locks.AbstractQueuedSynchronizer$ConditionObject@3473e980

I checked internally about these stack traces and this behaviour and came across a thread leak we had found in the code that was causing thousand (and in your cases tens of thousands) of these threads to show up and clog the machine
column2: eventually leading to the out of memory errors and failures across the board. I have compared your thread dump and errors with the ones we had reproduced and analyzed and everything was the same
column3: but that JIRA was fixed in 7.17.2 while you're on 7.25.7. It looks like there might be a regression here so I'm bringing this up to our developers to look into and if there's a temporary workaround while we check this out. This seems to only be happening on a single node but I don't have enough logs to confirm the other ones
column4: are you seeing the thread starvation or memory issues on any other nodes? Are all nodes on 7.25.7? If this is only happening on one node
column5: does turning off that one node fix the issue?

column1: 02s6900002PANoYAAX5006900003jaVkUAAU[#183869] Urgent: User is unable to access artifacts in apptio's JFrog artifactoryHello Team

Thank you for joining the session with us today during the session we tried to enable ( Local - Local) replication from on-prem to saas instance to push the local packages available in the on-prem PyPi local repository.
Since we do not have anyone available with "Admin" access during our session we were unable to complete the Replication.
As discussed please enable local to local replication from on-prem to saas following below steps:

Navigating to on-prem instance $Artifactory_UI --> Admin --> Repositories --> "PyPI local" --> Replication --> Add new replication by pointing the URL to Saas local repository ( created in our screen-sharing session )
Update the Saas instance Admin credentials in the "Username" and Password" fields.
Enable "Event" based Replciation so that the Artifacts will be synced and replicated between on-prem to a Saas.
Please configure the replication and revert back to us if you are facing any issues during the setup.
Looking forward to hearing from you.

02s6900002PANt9AAH5006900003jaiwEAAQ[#184105] Recent malicious code detected in ua-parser-js 0.7.29Hi Matt,

In regards to the UAParser.js package, I checked on the package and could see that the affected versions (0.7.29, 0.8.0, 1.0.0) are not available in the npm remote registry so unless this was downloaded before it was blocked, you will not be able to download the affected versions any more as they are deleted from the remote as seen here: https://www.npmjs.com/package/ua-parser-js.

As for the question on assigning a custom issue and then having that shown in the npm audit, it is possible. This functionality will be enabled by default on npm virtual repositories that aggregate at least one remote repository that supports npm audit. For example, a remote repository that points to https://registry.npmjs.org or Artifactory Smart Remote repository. I was able to test this on my side. I created a virtual repository test-npm that had a remote repository test-npm-remote pointing to https://registry.npmjs.org. Then I did an npm install of the ua-parser-js package. Since the current version does not have a vulnerability I did not see any security issue. I then assigned a custom critical issue to this package. Then uninstalled it from my local and then tried an install and could see this info:



I could also see the below info for npm audit which is provided by Xray:



I suspect that you have the npm remote repository set as the npm registry, please try once with the virtual repository and check if this works.

Looking forward to hearing from you.

Best regards,
Prasanna Narayana
JFrog Support

02s6900002PANt1AAH5006900003YgNt9AAF[#183561] Artifactory Upgrade ConfirmationHi Leo,

Thank you for your response.

Regarding the warning message about having multiple Artifactory instances connected to a single Xray instance, this was possible in the previous Artifactory 6.x and Xray 2.x versions. However, from Artifactory 7.x and Xray 3.x, it is not possible to connect Xray to multiple Artifactory instances. Xray must be connected to a single Artifactory instance.
As you're already using the 7.x & 3.x version of Artifactory and Xray, you can ignore the warning message and proceed with the upgrade.

I hope this answers your question. Please let me know if you have further questions and I will be glad to assist you.

Best regards,
Ino Choi
JFrog Support

02s6900002PANs2AAH5006900003Yg7cWAAR[#183209] pipelines not working after upgradeHi Sandeep,

Thank you for meeting with the Pipelines dev team and me today. We were able to provide an estimate on when two of the remaining UI concerns are going to be resolved, and I need to re-escalate the issue to the right team in order to make progress on the auto-refresh problem.

On the call we went over the main UI concerns. The Logs disappearing" and the "Lingering UI too zoomed in" UI issues are going to be resolved in the next upcoming patch for Pipelines. While it's hard to say when this fix is going to be released
column2: rest assured we are working towards resolving these specific issues.

column1: This leaves the remaining auto-refresh problem. Unfortunately there doesn't look to be any problem in the JFrog Pipelines application itself. The Pipelines dev team was unable to pin down why a 404 Not Found is being returned from the Router system.
Originally I had escalated this issue to the Router team
column2: but they told me to take it to the Pipelines team. On our call we produced hard evidence that there is a problem with the WebSocket protocol in particular. In our test
column3: we used a special curl command to simulate a "ws" protocol request.

column1: This request failed to reach the Pipelines Router when done through Artifactory. We also confirmed that regular HTTP / HTTPS requests are able to be handled
column2: this explains why the rest of the UI and build systems function as intended.

column1: Please let me know if you have any questions or concerns from our meeting today. I need to take these findings back to our Router dev team to determine the next steps. My hope is to have an update for you by either tomorrow or the day after that.

column5: you can create a watch and policy to generate violations. There are also reports you can create.

Regarding the node name in the UI
column2: we have confirmed that the parameter which displays in the UI of the artifactory monitoring page is the node-id that is set in the system-yaml.

column1: If the node-id is not set in the system-yaml it is calculated by the following:
The only possible way the value in system yaml gets replaced is if the environment variables are set manually.
Please note that if the above env variables are set then it will always get precedence over system yaml value set. Looking through the scripts you had sent we didn't see that this was set
column2: but we wanted to double check with you as this would explain the behavior.
we are currently focusing on this error:

column1: [31m[WARN ][0m [573db38906bd84d9] [join_executor.go:192          ] [main                ] - Cluster join: Error during cluster join: Error response from service registry
column2: status code: 409; message: Requested Router Join for nodeId: ec2fa5c68bbd773e56e902521cfc238d at: 10.233.10.86 conflicts (node id) with existing node: ServiceNodeImpl(serviceId=jffe@000
column4: routerId=ec2fa5c68bbd773e56e902521cfc238d

column1: After working with our r&d team we believe that this is the cause of the behavior. If a server is killed ungracefully - not allowing the server to unregister and
column2: then started again immediately (before the old entry of the topology is considered stale) which would result in access not allowing his router to register which would prevent startup. A simple "workaround" is to wait after ungraceful shutdown before starting the server again.

column1: This behavior would also explain the node.id name issue. The old entry isn't deleted because the shutdown wasn't graceful so the node didn't unregister from the topology
column2: which would cause the node id to change as there cannot be two nodes with the same node id. To confirm this please provide us with the shutdown process of the unhealthy node and how long you are waiting before spinning up the new node after shutting the old node off.

column1: Looking forward to hearing from you.

Response: If you are using Artifactory v7.x you can perform either of the below options in order to trust a new certificate:

2. Adding the certificate to the application's Java KeyStore.

column2: JFrog Support wrote:
we first discussed the usePresigning settings. The 5GB limit is on AWS single request limit and it can't be changed. For now
column3: we suggest to first disabling usePresigning setting in binarystore.xml.

column1: We also found out that there are some settings issues with buildInfo replication and after tunning the configDescriptors
column2: we are able to replicate buildInfo.
we are still seeing many 413 request entity too large error. We have modified tomcat and nginx settings but it still didn't help. Since we noticed that the disk space is filling up more than 95%
column3: we suggest to first trying to scale up disk space and artifactory could also throw 413 error when there's not enough diskspace.

column1: If you still see issues after disabling presigning and with enough disk space
column2: please reach out to us. Thank you.

02s6900002PAOAFAA55006900003YdlXsAAJRe: [#181523] System import fails following instructions for large system migrationThanks Scott. Looking forward to syncing up and figuring this out.

I have noticed that on the recent export i have been trying it is missing an access.bootstrap.json file which may explain why the identities info didn't get imported. I'm not sure if this is a consequence of disabling encryption before doing the export or not. We are looking into trying to get another export created to figure this out.

To queue up questions/issues to go over in the call i'll summarize what i believe are the high level ones here:Enabling/Disabling decryption on the source/target of export - Why is this needed at all? What are the consequences and risks to the source cluster (as that will be our current production instance in this case)The various routes that end up in javax.crypto.BadPaddingException errors (and if the KB article is even a reasonable workaround) (either immediately when the source still has encryption
column2: or after restart when not)Warnings or errors from mission control after import (either in release with 7.27.6 or or in separate release with 7.25.6)General concern for validity of our helm release configuration (values) related to the advanced usage docs around bootstrapping or other configWhat may cause exports to be missing access/identity configuration?Speed of import - Seems too slow for our initial plan as the downtime would probably be unacceptable so will probably need to eventually setup repo replication as well. But would like to figure out if there are other things we can tune or debug to identify bottleneck.

column2: Naveen
column4: and team

column1: Thank you for meeting with me again this morning. As I suspected
column2: there was a single remaining Conan file which failed to be migrated
column3: but we were able to complete the migration manually.

column1: We started by looking into the Permission Denied error I emailed you about this morning. This error looks to have been a red herring
column2: we found the checksum of the file in the error in the right "filestore" folder. As a precaution
column3: we granted the Artifactory application Windows Administrator access during the next reboot.

column2: we double checked the problem file mentioned in the artifactory-conan-v2-migration.log. We saw that indeed the "fm-conan:ennor/OmnitureFramework/3.69/stable" package hadn't been migrated
column3: and moved the folder under a "/0/" directory like the other versions.

column1: This worked when we did it manually. I am not sure why the automatic process failed on this single package at this time.

column2: we rebooted the application. Artifactory came online and the migration completed successfully pretty much right after. Conan builds and the API began working too.

column1: Please let me know if there are any remaining questions or concerns about our actions today. I'm glad things look to be working now
column2: and will check in if I don't hear back from you in a few days to make sure all is well.
