02s6900002PAOHfAAP5006900003jaiyFAAQRe: [#184109] XRAY not scanning newly added repoWill send you the xray one shortly.
These are part of watches as well as the indexed resources which I believe should get them scanned on its own?
I was able to resolve the problem yesterday haven’t checked to see yet if it reoccurred today.  We have 2 worker nodes and a dedicated DB VM for xray.  So 3 VMs involved for xray
I tried restarting the xray service on the second worker node.  This didn’t have any affect.  However
column2: I realized that some of the processes owned by xray had not restarted.  So I shutdown the service again and manually killed the processes that didn’t die.

column1: xray      6640     1  1 Oct01 ?        06:05:07 /usr/lib64/erlang/erts-10.7.2/bin/beam.smp -W w -K true -A 128 -MBas ageffcbf -MHas ageffcbf -MBlmbcs 512 -MHlmbcs 512 -MMmcs 30 -P 1048576 -t 5000000 -stbt db -zdbbl 128000 -B i -- -root /usr/lib64/erlang -progname erl -- -home /home/xray -- -pa  -noshell -noinput -s rabbit boot -boot start_sasl -lager crash_log false -lager handlers [] -noshell -noinput --

Then I started xray up again on that node and everything became  suddenly unstuck.  The load on both worker nodes shot up and everything started to get scanned.  In addition to the nuget-gallery that I added and realized wasn’t being scanned other repos were not scanning new artifacts.  We also cache docker hub and it only showed 60% of the artifacts scanned under indexed resources but this resolved as well after the service restart.
Xray was still providing data on artifacts that had already been scanned but it looked like no new artifacts were being scanned until the service restart on one of the worker nodes.
We are rolling out xray now to our users as a replacement for blackduck.  New artifacts silently not getting scanned is a real issue for us 😊
Will upload the xray support bundle in a few minutes but please let me know if you need anything else.  I really want to get to the bottom of what happened here.

column1: 02s6900002PAONEAA55006900003jaiw9AAA[#184104] Add 4th node with latest version to current clusterHi Pravin
It's actually a bit unstable adding an upgraded node as a new node to a cluster
column2: it can cause some issues and if a node needs to restart due to these issues it will fail to start up because of the DB changes made by the new node. In an HA cluster
column3: all nodes need to be the same version. The only time this changes is when you are upgrading a cluster. You would upgrade one node (that already exists in the cluster)
column4: then the system notices this version change and locks itself into only allowing uploads and downloads
column5: blocking all other config and DB changes. Some exceptions are thrown in the logs which is normal
column6: and everything returns to normal functionality and logging once all the nodes are upgraded. When you add a new node to a cluster that is already upgraded
column7: it can cause issues as it tries to set itself up by changing the DB and applying config but the cluster is getting locked at the same time and failures can occur.

column1: What you should do here to add a 4th node is upgrade the three existing nodes first to 7.25.7
column2: then add the fourth 7.25.7 node to the upgraded cluster. You can find the upgrade steps here https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Upgrading+Artifactory#UpgradingArtifactory-UpgradinganEnterpriseHACluster and the steps to add the new node afterwards here https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Installing+Artifactory#InstallingArtifactory-HAInstallation

I had set up a 7.12.8 HA cluster and attempted to add a 7.25.7 node it a few times. Often the primary node would fail which would cause the cluster to become damaged or the new node would fail and not be able to join the cluster due to the changes. Once I performed the upgrade and then added the node it went smoothly.

column1: You can't exactly correlate an Nginx request to a specific Artifactory log line. One of the major reasons why this is not possible is Artifactory's artifactory.log file does not make a log line for every single request. Instead
column2: this log file tracks the application's internal actions and behaviors
column3: which do not necessarily always correspond to a specific REST API action.

column1: It is usually possible to correlate a reverse proxy access.log event to the Artifactory request.log. From there
column2: I usually pull out the timestamp and search the artifactory.log for any events that happened within the application. There might be something
column4: depending on the context of the investigation.

column1: I had interpreted your original question to mean you wanted to track down a REST API action through the network. If you provided me with more details around what you are trying to accomplish
column2: I could assist further. I look forward to your reply.

column2: we looked at the failures from your CLI upload. We first checked the artifactory-request.log and saw we were able to see each upload attempt
column3: which would include a 404 (checking if the file exists) and then a 201. Looking at the CLI logs it showed a 404 failure on two files. When we looked for these files we saw they were .md5 files
column4: which led me to believe this JIRA https://www.jfrog.com/jira/browse/RTFACT-25199 was the cause. Looking at the error message we confirmed we were getting the same error
column5: and after running a few more tests we could see the issue was only happening to files with the .md5 extension. You can change the extension as a workaround (i.e. file.md5.buildname) so the upload succeeds
column6: though you would have to change it back after to work with it if a project is hard coded to find that specific filename or parses files by their extension.

column2: I'm going to go ahead and push this JIRA internally to see what the current status of it is.

column1: 02s6900002PAORzAAP5006900003MofpLAAR[#179068] Docker container upload and download issues.Hi Veronica
Thank you for taking the time to speak with me today.

column2: we discussed the steps taken prior to today’s session:

column1: Tested the docker push to the AWS Artifactory instance instead of the Azure Artifactory instance
Saw an improvement in upload speeds
column2: but still saw issues with uploads over 10 minutes
setting the timeout to 20 minutes
column3: but still seeing issues with uploads to the afmc-jomsmvp-docker-readyfortest repository

column1: Tested uploading the images with the JFrog CLI instead of curl

column2: we tested an upload to a different repository on the Azure Artifactory instance.  When running the docker push artifact.dev.azure.cce.af.mil/afmc-jomsmvp-docker-readyforprod/geoserver:2.5.7-plus-650M command
column3: we were able to reproduce the initial error with the 1ba10df725a5 layer.  We saw that the layer would push past the calculated 650 MB
column4: retry

column1: This may not be a size issue since we saw the same behavior for a 650 MB layer and a 1.016 GB layer.
This may not be an Nginx timeout issue since the layer took 18 minutes to push before restarting

column2: good question. I believe it's possible to convert back to a local repository
column3: and after testing it on my side have drafted a procedure you can use while we investigate the problem.

column2: the safest method of rolling back to local repositories is to create a new local repository
column4: and then using the JFrog CLI to move the packages out of "scaligent" to "scaligent-local":

column2: as you might have development teams which cannot change repository names easily. In that case
column3: rolling back a Local -> Federated conversion involves the following process:

column1: 0] Click the "Copy/Paste" button in the upper right hand corner of the Artifactory -> Advanced -> Config Descriptor menu
column2: this copies the entire Configuration Descriptor  to your clipboard. Please save a backup copy of the working configuration before proceeding.
empty local repository called "scaligent-2" via the normal UI process
column3: we will be changing the name in a later step

column1: 2] Go back to the Artifactory -> Advanced -> Config Descriptor menu and cut out the "<federatedRepository>" configuration section - Do not click save yet

column2: navigate to the new "scaligent-2" <localRepository> XML block. Change the "scaligent-2" localRepository key to be "scaligent".
you should see a success message. If not
column3: click the"Reset" and let me know.

column1: Artifactory will map the artifacts from the Federated "scaligent" repository to this new local repository
column2: essentially rolling it back to a local repository.

column1: You can then proceed with setting up Push replications on the repository to push files to a remote URL. You can re-convert back to a Federated repository later
column2: for all intents and purposes the repository type has changed back to a Local.

column2: I started to check our release notes to see what sort of docker changes there were between the 7.23.X version and your current 6.23.28 version. I found that in the Artifactory 7.11.7 Release Notes
column3: we noted a JIRA(RTFACT-25912) that resolved an issue with the new way Docker Hub implemented HTTP which affected response headers. If you review the JIRA

column5: as well as a multitude of other patches for different Artifactory versions.

column3: I reproduced the same behavior you're experiencing. When I tested these image downloads on the 7.11.7 instance
column4: I was able to successfully pull both the images without any errors. I spun up one last instance to ensure that post 7.11.7 this issue does not re-surface. In the new instance (7.12.6) the issue was not present and both images pulled without any issues.

column1: After working with our r&d team we believe that this is the cause of the behavior. If a server is killed ungracefully - not allowing the server to unregister and
column2: then started again immediately (before the old entry of the topology is considered stale) which would result in access not allowing his router to register which would prevent startup. A simple "workaround" is to wait after ungraceful shutdown before starting the server again.

column1: This behavior would also explain the node.id name issue. The old entry isn't deleted because the shutdown wasn't graceful so the node didn't unregister from the topology
column2: which would cause the node id to change as there cannot be two nodes with the same node id. To confirm this please provide us with the shutdown process of the unhealthy node and how long you are waiting before spinning up the new node after shutting the old node off.

column1: 02s6900002PAOYlAAP5006900003jagHEAAY[#184039] Signed virtual repository cache length and bustingHello Alex
Thank you for the reply and clarification. As Aritfactory utilizes a checksum-based storage system for validation
column2: it does not natively perform jar-signing nor update appended signature files that have been uploaded to local repositories. Consequently
column3: there is no set Time-To-Live value associated with uploaded signature files as well; the uploaded signature file is stored as initially deployed and not cached. I hope this does provide some clarity. Please let me know if you have additional questions regarding this as we will be happy to assist however possible.

column1: 02s6900002PAObkAAH5006900003jaV10AAE[#183844] How to connect  a http request in reverse proxy  log to artifactory log. is there a sessionid or something that can be added in artifactory log
column2: to easily map ?Hi Rajasekaran

column1: I understand the challenge involved when there is a complex deployment. I wanted to understand the problem better before recommending a path forward here.
In Artifactory 7.X a new column was introduced to the log files
column2: the "trace ID" field is used to track events across different log files:

column1: Timestamp | Trace ID | Remote Address | Username | Request method | Request URL | Return Status | Request Content Length | Response Content Length | Request Duration | Request User Agent
Timestamp (UTC) [Service Type] [Level] [Trace Id] [Class and Line Number] [Thread] - Message
This is what we control within JFrog applications' logging.
Do you have any suggestions about what could be added to Artifactory or our products to log an external tracking ID
column2: such as one from an Nginx reverse proxy? I personally can't think of a good way to track an external request of this nature beyond the pattern matching technique I described earlier.

column1: You can always create an account on our Public JIRA to fill out the details of a new feature. I would suggest including your use case and any details such as the reverse proxy type we need to add this compatibility for.
Please see the attached. I will be available till 5.00 AM IST.

Xray has undergone a number of updates with performance improvements and I would recommend an upgrade to the latest version of Xray if able.

The high CPU usage is just because Xray is very busy with indexing a lot of binaries when the copy to the Xray indexed repository was done. This is expected as it is a heavy load that Xray has to work through.
There is some tuning that can be done (reference for xray 2.X but still has relevant for 3.X).

Regarding the log collection (an Xray support bundle?) I am not certain what may be causing the issue. Could you attempt to generate another support bundle and if/when it fails go ahead and zip up the Xray log directory and send it to me?

02s6900002PAOcEAAX5006900003YgU4OAAV[#183668] Intermittent 403 errors when Buildkit attempts to publish Docker images to ArtifactoryHi Matthew
Thanks for sending over the bundle and providing the information.  Looking into the logs
column2: we do see a lot of these DENIED DOWNLOAD requests within the Artifactory access logs.  We have seen similar issues and would like to try updating a system property that could be blocking this token when attempting to authenticate.

column1: We can set the artifactory.security.maxLoginBlockDelay=0 in the artifactory.system.properties.  This setting defaults to 5 seconds and blocks a user or token for a period of time when there are issues with authentication.  This will require a restart of the cluster
column2: but should play a role in the issue we are seeing.  You can then monitor the instance to see if we see further 403s for the builds.  Looking forward to hearing from you with the results.

02s6900002PAOePAAX5006900003janr7AAA[#184209] JFrog sending 502 response to GitHub webhook integrationHi Joshua

I'd like to update you that we observed the pipeline service in crashloop due to some builds that won’t be kicked off if head.repo field in the PR webhook event is null. This can happen if a git repository with open PRs got deleted and if buildOn.pullRequestClose is set to true in the corresponding gitRepo resource configuration.
We have an internal Jira related to this issue: PIPE-7175 and the ETA for a permanent fix is tomorrow. We deployed a workaround to make the pipeline service stable until the permanent fix is released
column2: and in order to avoid this issue occurring again until tomorrow
column3: I request you to check the above-mentioned condition (i.e some builds that won’t be kicked off if head.repo field in the PR webhook event is null. This can happen if a git repository with open PRs got deleted and if buildOn.pullRequestClose is set to true in the corresponding gitRepo resource configuration) which leads the pipeline service to crash.

Subject: [EXTERNAL] [#183508] Issues with pypi remote smart repository not indexing packages
For your issue with the Monitaur package:
I took a look at the logs and noticed that Artifactory is checking all the repositories for the 1.0.0 but in the .whl format and getting a 404 from all sources:

2021 @ 19:49:45.353    2021-10-19T19:49:45.353Z|546fa2e3684c3db8|170.218.219.22|a097589|GET|/api/nativeBrowser/pgr-pypi/monitaur/1.0.0/monitaur-1.0.0-py3-none-any.whl|404|2|0|14|Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML

2021 @ 19:49:45.352    2021-10-19T19:49:45.352Z|546fa2e3684c3db8|monitaur-remote|progressive|GET|https://monitaur.jfrog.io/artifactory/monitaur-pypi-local/monitaur/1.0.0/monitaur-1.0.0-py3-none-any.whl/|404|0|0|9

column1: It is then defaulting back to the latest version available in .whl which happens to be 0.27.0 on pypi.org
For the successful 1.0.0 downloads I see the filename of the package listed as monitaur-1.0.0.tar.gz
So it doesn't look like the newer version of the package just exists as sources and pip is preferring the wheel.
If you download with "--no-binary" are you still getting 0.27.0?

02s6900002PAOetAAH5006900003YfEt0AAF[#182516] Artifactory:  trying to reconcile metadata (db binaries / file objects)Hi Michael
Can you run a diff of the entries in the binaries table and the files in your file store? Then
column2: with the sha1 value of the binaries in the diff
column3: we can run a checksum search to see what artifacts the extra binaries correspond with.

column1: 1. Get a list of binaries from Artifactory's database by querying sha1 values from "binaries" table
a. SELECT sha1 FROM binaries Order By sha1 ASC;
b. save the output as a file
2. Get a list of binaries from Artifactory's filestore.
a. Go to Artifactory's filestore folder (e.g. ../ha-data/filestore/)
3. Find the differences between the results above using your favorite diff tool

column1: 02s6900002PAOfrAAH5006900003Ydf8NAAR[#181374] Please advise - Xray admin user login troubleshooting - ThanksHi Tyler
Thank you for joining today's meeting with me and Anand.

column2: we were able to see that there was a problem logging in to the Xray UI as an Xray admin user.
and we also disabled Artifactory to act as the Authentication Provider.

column1: Then we were able to login as Xray admin user to Xray UI using the non-local cached session.

column2: we were able to create a new user and give it the admin privilege on the Xray UI by navigating to Admin->Permissions->Permission Name->Users->select the user to have the "Admin" privilege.

column1: We were also able to see that we could login as the newly-created user that had a full admin access.

column2: I will go ahead and close this ticket. If you have further questions regarding this issue
column3: you can reopen this ticket by replying to this email thread. I'd be happy to assist you further.

02s6900002PAOjFAAX5006900003jaocUAAQRe: [#184250] Inconsistent Conda package installation - missing later package versionsHi Jfrog support team
column2: We observe an inconsistent conda package behavior which some latest/higher versions of a package is not installed properly. This missing behavior is not universal
column3: only affect to some package sometimes. In the past
column4: we reindexed conda repos to resolve the issue but this fix does not seem to be effective anymore. This behavior is observed in both Artifactory 6 and Artifactory 7# Download the environment.yml file from https://github.cloud.capitalone.com/raw/creditflow/legoland_creditflow/main/environments/limopclip_frozen.yml -o environment.yml that list all the dependencies for the conda package

column1: # Create conda enviromnent where we will install the "limopclip" conda package.
# We want to install the latest conda package of "limopclip".

column2: which is NOT the latest release of the package.

column1: # The latest release of the conda package is limopclip-2021.08.18-1. It's on Artifactory and is downloadable.
# Issue is that `current_repodata.json` is not up to date
column2: and does not list the actual latest release of the conda package.

column1: # which returns "limopclip-2021.08.18-py_0.tar.bz2" and not the expected latest package "limopclip-2021.08.18_1-py_0.tar.bz2"
Please check "environment.yml" and the console log file (conda-install.log) of the installation scenario attached to this thread for more details.
The support bundle is also uploaded to this thread.

column1: 02s6900002PAOjeAAH5006900003jamNWAAYRE: [#184180] URGENT - unable to upload build info when working in "project" modeHi

column2: Adrian

column1: Not having support for the “Projects and Roles” feature in the Jenkins Artifactory plugin???
Some drama here… I’m discovering this in the middle of a migration of a project from Artifactory v6 to Artifactory v7… I am a bit shocked…

We probably don’t see this in the same eyes… so I’m raising this for you: I think that Jfrog is not understanding the significance of this “small detail”. I’m afraid this is not going to make Jfrog’s product look good.
You manage to deliver amazing functionality and here because of a single simple parameter that is not implemented all the way
column2: I am finding myself pulling my hair in the middle of a pipeline migration.

column1: I promised my users that migrating to version 7 would be better for them in every sense. I really trust Jfrog’s product and its maturity. And I’m definitely not the first one jumping onto the version 7 wagon
column2: so I’m totally not ready for this . This seems like an issue that should have been worked out long ago.

column1: I played around with the projects and roles functionality of Artifactory version 7 and decided its good and worth a try.
I would never think that you did not cover this functionality from all the aspects.
Is there a warning somewhere? Saying that projects and roles don’t support uploading build info in case you are using the Jenkins Artifactory plugin???
Now this is going to cause many Jenkins jobs to fail because of failing to upload the build info
column2: because the field for specifying the “project” name is not implemented.

column1: I’m not familiar with the complexity of adding this parameter but it seems like a trivial optional parameter that you can add…
So for now I worked out the permission issue by adding a new permission target that allows the relevant generic user to read/upload/delete build info for all the repos.
Its not good because it allows the people in one project to delete builds of another... but I am going to have to allow this risk for now.
So the build info made it to the “artifactory-build-info” repo and the Jenkins job is successful.

All the work I put in setting up project roles is not covering me… now I need to do double provisioning… I need to add users into the project roles AND ALSO in to the workaround permission target so they can upload build info.
Now I need to somehow MOVE the relevant build info entries from the artifactory-build-info repo into the antip-build-info repo (which is dedicated to the “antip” project).
So now I have to script some magic that will do this moving behind the scenes…
This is not the only project on the server… so I am going to run into this with other projects as well… this is not fun!

Even if I do manage to script that (in the middle of a migration???) still the link to the build info in the Jenkins job will be broken… because the build info was moved to a different repo … so perhaps I should just copy it… I don’t want to do all of that!!!
Now I need to communicate this complexity to my users… to whom I promised a better platform…

This is not the end of the world but it is really un-expected at this time and seems to me to be a big miss on Jfrog’s part to ship this functionality as “production ready” but not to cover this functionality from end to end!

Supposing I tell my users to turn off the checkbox to “collect and upload build info” in their Jenkins jobs. What workaround can be implemented to cover that functionality outside the Jenkins Artifactory plugin?
some are maven jobs and some are Jenkins pipelines.
How I do we tell Jenkins to collect build info and upload it to the build info repository of the project? can you send me code that covers that?

I’m starting to think that its better for me to stop using projects and roles and revert to the old way of managing groups and permission targets. This takes me out of this issue in the fastest way and allows me to complete the migration without all this extra trouble … Do you agree?
Subject: [#184180] URGENT - unable to upload build info when working in "project" mode
I missed your last email before I asked for the Support Bundle.
Regarding the use of Projects within the Jenkins Plugin
column2: currently there’s no ETA on when this functionality will be implemented. Therefore
column3: if you would like to continue to use the Jenkins plugin
column4: the way to implement this now with Projects is via the following steps:

column1: 1.  Publish the build normally to artifactory-build-info (the default repository where all build info has been stored until now).

2. 3.  Delete<https://gbr01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.jfrog.com%2Fconfluence%2Fdisplay%2FJFROG%2FArtifactory%2BREST%2BAPI%23ArtifactoryRESTAPI-DeleteBuilds&data=04%7C01%7Camitron%40synamedia.com%7Cffd4593f54ab4993975708d99886dccc%7Cecdd899a33be4c3391e41f1144fc2f56%7C0%7C0%7C637708527260085696%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&sdata=54gxy8hCucgzqesMEN3tJ6OIp9cgu0j%2BsYj9R%2Bk3E74%3D&reserved=0> the existing build info JSON in artifactory-build-info

column2: artifactory-build-info is the default repository where all build information is published when a Project isn't specified. If a build is published to a Project
column3: the build-info will be located in a repository with the following name: <project-key>-build-info.

column2: you can restructure the pipeline to use the JFrog CLI<https://gbr01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.jfrog.com%2Fconfluence%2Fdisplay%2FCLI%2FCLI%2Bfor%2BJFrog%2BArtifactory%23CLIforJFrogArtifactory-PublishingBuild-Info&data=04%7C01%7Camitron%40synamedia.com%7Cffd4593f54ab4993975708d99886dccc%7Cecdd899a33be4c3391e41f1144fc2f56%7C0%7C0%7C637708527260095647%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&sdata=rsQxHRUthmfxFaA4rNMTD9y0Iz%2F%2BJ24h90gM1qaBOGc%3D&reserved=0> or API<https://gbr01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.jfrog.com%2Fconfluence%2Fdisplay%2FJFROG%2FArtifactory%2BREST%2BAPI%23ArtifactoryRESTAPI-BuildUpload&data=04%7C01%7Camitron%40synamedia.com%7Cffd4593f54ab4993975708d99886dccc%7Cecdd899a33be4c3391e41f1144fc2f56%7C0%7C0%7C637708527260095647%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&sdata=FabGmDavMja9j%2B8UcZ5y9iVVo7gIf9eDKLKSbqdBi%2Fw%3D&reserved=0> which both support the Project option.

02s6900002PAOjkAAH5006900003YecveAAB[#182141] Migrating data from Artifactory 6.x to 7.xHello Jun

These look like pods that were generated and brought down. These entries do get cleaned up automatically but it does take a while. (The nodes get set stale after 7 days from a successful heartbeat and there is an hourly cleanup job that removes the stale nodes.)

Checking internally not being able to remove the nodes from the UI appears to be a known issue (internal JIRA JFUI-7605 - "Unable to delete offline Artifactory nodes(7.27.3) from Service Status page"). This issue is still being reviewed and there is no ETA for this as of now.
If you wish to have the nodes get set stale faster (and get cleaned up faster) you can configure these configurations.
consider-stale-seconds: 604800 # the time period (seconds) since the last heartbeat was registered in the topology
column2: so is considered stale

column1: If you are interested in a lower setting I would recommend setting this to be 1 hour (3600). These configurations do not appear by default so you will have to add these to the file.
This change can be done by changing the access.config yml file
# To change the configuration in an Access service
column2: follow these instructions:

column1: # 1. Find the value you want to update (the snippet I mentioned above)
# 2. Set the value in the access.config.latest.yml file under [$JFROG_HOME]/artifactory/var/etc/access
Another example can be found in the wiki page: https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Access+YAML+Configuration#AccessYAMLConfiguration-UploadingtheYAMLFile

column1: 02s6900002PAOmYAAX5006900003jajBYAAY[#184120] Artifactory support for S3 lifecycle rules and AWS GlacierHi Farhaan
Thank you for contacting JFrog Support.

column2: please see the below

column1: I wanted to confirm the artifactory support for S3 life cycle rules like migrating the artifact to AWS Glacier (cold storage) if it's not downloaded in a specified period of time and putting it back to S3 if the user requests it at any point of time.

column2: Artifactory supports migrating artifacts to Cold Storage instance like AWS Glacier. Once Cold Artifactory instance is set up
column3: you can set up retention policies to archive unused artifacts or restore them on demand. Please see the below links for more information.

column1: Subject: RE: [#183808] UST SmartOps - optimization calculation

“The binary size displayed is the storage occupied IF there was no deduplication. The artifact size is the true amount of storage occupied in the binarystore (the filesystem physically storing the artifacts).”

column2: I wonder why the storage watermark used the binary size (which is hypothetical) and not the artifact size (which is real).

column1: Artifact size never went above 1.5 GB throughout this month. The graph above from billing portal exactly reflected the binary size reported for each day. I hope the billing will be based on actual usage and not hypothetical usage.

column2: IN) <Raman.Divakaran@ust.com>; logand@jfrog.com

column1: EXTERNAL EMAIL - Do not click any links or open any attachments unless you trust the sender and know the content is safe.
The checksum based storage functions as a method of deduplication.

The binary size displayed is the storage occupied IF there was no deduplication. The artifact size is the true amount of storage occupied in the binarystore (the filesystem physically storing the artifacts).
So if you have a 100MB artifact in two repositories your binary size would show 200MB but since both repositories refer to the same artifact in the binarystore your artifact size is only 100MB.
Please feel free to let us know if there are any questions regarding this.

lines are saying is that the DB conversion step v60 failed. Artifactory goes through a bunch of steps to validate the DB
column2: and then perform changes on an upgrade. These are all labeled v1 to v200+. Each one is a bundle of a few SQL queries to perform. In this case
column3: the issue is that the replication_errors table doesn't exist so the checks on it can't be done. You would do this on the postgres container attached to Artifactory.

column1: Here are some of the reasons why builds are receiving error message 502 bad gateway
The POM misses the declaration of the <repository> which hosts the artifact.
The repository you have configured requires authentication and Maven failed to provide the correct credentials to the server. In this case
column2: make sure your ${user.home}/.m2/settings.xml contains a <server> declaration whose <id> matches the <id> of the remote repository to use. See the Maven Settings Reference for more details.

column1: The remote repository in question uses SSL and the JVM running Maven does not trust the certificate of the server.
There is a general network problem that prevents Maven from accessing any remote repository
column2: e.g. a missing proxy configuration.

column1: You have configured Maven to perform strict checksum validation and the files to download got corrupted.
Maven failed to save the files to your local repository
column2: see LocalRepositoryNotAccessibleException for more details.

column1: 02s6900002PAOu8AAH5006900003janQvAAI[#184200] Include/exclude pattern settings issue in Artifactory.Hi Jessie
Thanks for taking the time to meet with me today. In our session
column2: we were able to resolve the issue described - encountering a "rejected the artifact due to its include/exclude pattern setting" error when attempting to upload artifacts with the symbol '~' at the end of the filename. In order to resolve this
column3: we removed pattern '**/*~' from the artifactory.repo.includeExclude.globalExcludes property within the artifactory.system.properties file and then restarted Artifactory.  We tested and confirmed that we could now upload (and download) the files in question.

column1: As for the error that we were seeing in the logs during our session
column2: I do not believe that this error is a result of the change in system properties. The below error is received when Artifactory's Password Encryption Policy is set to 'Required' and there are users attempting to authenticate against Artifactory using plain text passwords.

column2: what the

column1: Caused by: org.jfrog.converter.DbConverterRuntimeException: Failed to convert v60
Caused by: org.postgresql.util.PSQLException: ERROR: relation "replication_errors" does not exist
lines are saying is that the DB conversion step v60 failed. Artifactory goes through a bunch of steps to validate the DB
column2: and then perform changes on an upgrade. These are all labeled v1 to v200+. Each one is a bundle of a few SQL queries to perform. In this case
column3: the issue is that the replication_errors table doesn't exist so the checks on it can't be done. We are creating the table (as it should be there) so it can validate it exists and perform any edits to the table as we continue the migration. You would do this on the postgres container attached to Artifactory.

github.com/stash-core/database-tools/pkg/transaction: cannot find module providing package github.com/stash-core/database-tools/pkg/transaction: module github.com/stash-core/database-tools/pkg/transaction: reading https://stash-core-local-dev:xxxxx@stash.jfrog.io/artifactory/api/go/stash-core-go/github.com/stash-core/database-tools/pkg/transaction/@v/list: 404 Not Found

column2: so you won't be able to see it
column3: however this path does exist: https://github.com/stash-core/database-tools/tree/main/pkg/transaction and the "stash-core-github-remote" Repository in Artifactory is configured with a username/token that has access to the repository.

column1: The current workaround is to set GOPRIVATE to "github.com/stash-core"
column2: but this defeats the purpose of using Artifactory. We'd like all downloads to go through Artifactory.

column1: > time this changes is when you are upgrading a cluster. You would upgrade
> one node (that already exists in the cluster)
column2: then the system notices this

column1: > version change and locks itself into only allowing uploads and downloads

column1: > logging once all the nodes are upgraded. When you add a new node to a
